{{Expand Japanese|ニコチンアミドモノヌクレオチド|date=September 2018}} {{Chembox <!-- Images --> | ImageFile = Nicotinamide mononucleotide.svg | ImageSize = 200px | ImageAlt = <!-- Names --> | IUPACName = 3-Carbamoyl-1-[5-''O''-(hydroxyphosphinato)-β-<small>D</small>-ribofuranosyl]pyridinium | OtherNames = {{unbulleted list | Nicotinamide ribonucleoside 5'-phosphate | Nicotinamide <small>D</small>-ribonucleotide | β-Nicotinamide ribose monophosphate| Nicotinamide nucleotide }} <!-- Sections --> | Section1 = {{Chembox Identifiers | CASNo = 1094-61-7 | PubChem = 16219737 | ChemSpiderID = 13553 | SMILES = c1cc(c[n+](c1)[C@H]2[C@@H]([C@@H]([C@H](O2)COP(=O)(O)[O-])O)O)C(=O)N | StdInChI = 1S/C11H15N2O8P/c12-10(16)6-2-1-3-13(4-6)11-9(15)8(14)7(21-11)5-20-22(17,18)19/h1-4,7-9,11,14-15H,5H2,(H3-,12,16,17,18,19)/t7-,8-,9-,11-/m1/s1 | StdInChIKey = DAYLJWODMCOQEW-TURQNECASA-N }} | Section2 = {{Chembox Properties | C=11|H=15|N=2|O=8|P=1 | Appearance = | Density = | MeltingPt = | BoilingPt = | Solubility = }} | Section3 = {{Chembox Hazards | MainHazards = | FlashPt = | AutoignitionPt = }} }}
'''Nicotinamide mononucleotide''' ("'''NMN'''" and "'''β-NMN'''") is a [[nucleotide]] derived from [[ribose]] and [[nicotinamide]].<ref name=Bogan2008/> Like [[nicotinamide riboside]], NMN is a derivative of [[niacin]], and humans have enzymes that can use NMN to generate [[nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide]] (NADH).<ref name=Bogan2008>{{cite journal|last1=Bogan|first1=KL|last2=Brenner|first2=C|title=Nicotinic acid, nicotinamide, and nicotinamide riboside: a molecular evaluation of NAD+ precursor vitamins in human nutrition.|journal=Annual Review of Nutrition|date=2008|volume=28|pages=115–30|doi=10.1146/annurev.nutr.28.061807.155443|pmid=18429699}}</ref>
Because NADH is a [[Cofactor (biochemistry)|cofactor]] for processes inside [[mitochondria]], for [[sirtuin]]s, and for [[Poly (ADP-ribose) polymerase|PARP]], NMN has been studied in [[animal model]]s as a potential neuroprotective and [[anti-aging]] agent.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Brazill|first1=JM|last2=Li|first2=C|last3=Zhu|first3=Y|last4=Zhai|first4=RG|title=NMNAT: It's an NAD<sup>+</sup> synthase… It's a chaperone… It's a neuroprotector.|journal=Current Opinion in Genetics & Development|date=June 2017|volume=44|pages=156–162|doi=10.1016/j.gde.2017.03.014|pmid=28445802|pmc=5515290}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Long-Term Administration of Nicotinamide Mononucleotide Mitigates Age-Associated Physiological Decline in Mice|journal=Cell Metabolism|date=13 December 2016|url=https://www.cell.com/cell-metabolism/fulltext/S1550-4131(16)30495-8}}</ref> Dietary supplement companies have [[Hard sell|aggressively marketed]] NMN products claiming those benefits,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stipp|first1=David|title=Beyond Resveratrol: The Anti-Aging NAD Fad|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/guest-blog/beyond-resveratrol-the-anti-aging-nad-fad |work=[[Scientific American]] Blog Network |date=March 11, 2015|language=en}}</ref><ref name=Bigley>Bigley, Sharon, ''[https://www.statnews.com/2018/03/22/dietary-supplement-makes-old-mice-spry/ A dietary supplement makes old mice youthful. But will it work in people?]'', STAT, March 22, 2018 '''(paywalled)'''</ref> though there is no clinical study on humans published yet.<ref name=Bigley/>
